tps://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman with known gallstones is admitted with a two-day history of jaundice and right upper quadrant pain. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, her pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is normal. Urine and blood samples are collected for laboratory analysis. An upper abdominal ultrasound is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most in keeping with this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urobilinogen but no conjugated bilirubin in the urine","Urobilinogen and conjugated bilirubin in the urine","A conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia and bilirubinuria","High levels of conjugated bilirubin and transaminases in the serum","High levels of unconjugated bilirubin and urobilinogen in the urine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound examination shows a stone in the common bile duct. Jaundice associated with stones in the common bile duct (ie. choledocholithiasis) suggests that the duct has become obstructed, leading to a predominantly \u003Cstrong\u003Econjugated hyperbilirubinaemia.\u003C/strong\u003E Normally, conjugated bilirubin is excreted into the gut through the bile duct and is converted into urobilinogen by bacterial enzymes in the gut. A part of it is reabsorbed into the blood while the rest is excreted in the form of stercobilin (the final bilirubin product in the gut that gives the stools a characteristic brown colour). A large percentage of the reabsorbed urobilinogen that is absorbed is recycled to bile in the liver while the remaining is excreted through urine. Patients with choledocholithiasis have an obstruction within the bile duct that does not allow the excretion of bile into the gut. This leads to pale stools due to a lack of stercobilin. The obstruction causes the conjugated bilirubin to spill into the bloodstream, hence leading to hyperbilirubinemia. Since conjugated bilirubin is water-soluble, high levels of conjugated bilirubin are excreted through urine (ie, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebilirubinuria\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrobilinogen and no conjugated bilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E in the urine is a normal finding in healthy patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPresence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eurobilinogen and conjugated bilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E in the urine may be seen in non-obstructive liver diseases (eg, viral hepatitis). Urobilinogen will likely be absent or decreased in patients with obstructive jaundice since bilirubin would not be converted into urobilinogen in the gut.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh levels of \u003Cstrong\u003Econjugated bilirubin and transaminases in the serum \u003C/strong\u003Eis a likely finding in liver diseases. Choledocholithiasis is associated with high levels of conjugated bilirubin in the serum. However, transaminases may be normal or mildly elevated in most early cases since choledocholithiasis is primarily a pathology in the bile duct and would be associated with predominantly elevated alkaline phosphatase, NOT transaminases (ie, aspartate aminotransferase, alanine aminotransferase).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnconjugated bilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E is not water-soluble and would not be seen in the urine. The presence of urobilinogen in the urine is a normal finding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Jaundice associated with stones in the common bile duct (ie, choledocholithiasis) suggests that the duct has become obstructed, leading to a predominantly conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia."],"references":["Fargo MV, Grogan SP, Saguil A. Evaluation of Jaundice in Adults. Am Fam Physician. 2017; 95:164-68"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14568"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14568"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eeca29a-c510-4c61-962a-2f0917b88d2a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eeca29a-c510-4c61-962a-2f0917b88d2a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":427}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-26T06:41:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-26T06:41:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"814"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42925"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a